    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "ae3be5ab_85d06ece",
        "filename": "buildbucket/proto/project_config.proto",
        "patchSetId": 1
      },
      "lineNbr": 466,
      "author": {
        "id": 1001907
      },
      "writtenOn": "2020-05-29T06:26:48Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "\u003e FWIU this field is temporary because soon we delete kitchen. Is this field going to be removed?\n\nI think when we remove this we can just mark it as deprecated and ignore it.\n\n\u003e are we going to send PSA asking people to remove usage of this field?\n\nSure; if they were proactive enough to set it in the first place, then I would expect them to be able to remove it as well. The purpose here is to allow proactive teams to control the rollout of the feature. Reactive teams won\u0027t ever bother setting this.\n\n\u003e I remember it took a year to remove vpython-native tag completely because it was sitting in user configs and I am worried we will not to timely follow up again because it is busy work.\n\u003e \n\nWe\u0027re still controlling the \u0027default\u0027 rollout via settings.cfg. \n\nAt some point we\u0027ll switch \"UNSET\" to mean kitchen, and then subsequently we\u0027ll ignore this field entirely. I think this is a bit different than vpython.\n\nAt some point we\u0027ll force-convert all opted-out configurations to bbagent.\n\nI\u0027m thinking about adding a way for buildbucket to attach warnings to a build, too, which would help surface this to the relevant eyeballs.\n\n\u003e this was the reason why bb_agent switch is done in the global settings.cfg which we control 100% and can update at any time.\n\nThe downside of this is that users cannot reasonably modify settings.cfg, meaning that we have to hand-hold all users, deal with reverts and conflicts, etc.",
      "parentUuid": "83b37d09_f587f19e",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 466,
        "startChar": 25,
        "endLine": 466,
        "endChar": 36
      },
      "revId": "c60d300046f10b58a1d066d4947b5fd0eb7a3810",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": true
