      },
      "lineNbr": 466,
      "author": {
        "id": 1114299
      },
      "writtenOn": "2020-05-29T20:04:41Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "yes, this would address my concern, thanks 😊 since we are talking about generalizations ;)...\n\nsome time ago Yuke needed to roll out a new experiment: exoneration of flaky tests, and see how it changes time duration. Correlating this with time of change rollout was very noisy, so instead he generated a random number in the recipe, conditionally enabled the experiment, and recorded the boolean in the output property. Then he used BQ to see how much better builds with the experiment perform.\n\nnote that this does not need to be related to canary. Essentially, the problem with \"canary\" is that it is a single boolean, as opposed to a *set* of experiments. With a set, different teams would be able to conduct their own experiments (like Finch?) and do A-B comparisons, independently. \n\nso, we might want to consider a mapping from arbitrary experiment name to percentage at the builder level, and then a set of enabled experiments at the build level. \"bbagent\" would be one of them, and it would have a server-defined default.\n\nOr maybe \"$bbagent\" with \"$\" meaning reserved to LUCI stuff.",
      "parentUuid": "9d8e4a94_384444f3",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 466,
        "startChar": 25,
        "endLine": 466,
        "endChar": 36
      },
      "revId": "c60d300046f10b58a1d066d4947b5fd0eb7a3810",
